entry.title: Make IdentityUrlLoaderThrottle work on non-main thread
entry.content:
Currently IdentityUrlLoaderThrottle is not created by

URLLoaderThrottleProvider when CreateThrottles() is called on non-main

thread. So IdentityUrlLoaderThrottle don't work for subresource requests

from workers. This is not a big issue since login and logout requests

are rarely sent by workers.



But it will be a problen when we will call CreateThrottles() of a cloned

URLLoaderThrottleProvider on the background thread for normal

subresource requests from frames for BackgroundResourceFetch feature

(crrev.com/c/5113665).





So this CL does followings:

1. Keep the main thread task runner in providers

(URLLoaderThrottleProviderImpl and

ShellContentRendererUrlLoaderThrottleProvider).

2. Make CreateThrottles() method of the providers create

IdentityUrlLoaderThrottle even when it is called on non-main thread.

3. In the callback of MaybeCreateIdentityUrlLoaderThrottle, use the

main thread task runner to call blink::SetIdpSigninStatus() in the

main thread when the callback is called on non-main thread.



Low-Coverage-Reason: COVERAGE_UNDERREPORTED

entry.title: Warms up service worker after service worker is stopped
entry.content:
This CL adds a new trigger for service worker warm-up. The service

worker can stop very early if there were no service worker API

calls. For example, if a service worker only registers a fetch event,

the service worker can stop after 30 seconds from the last fetch event

handling. I think this is the main reason why the service worker warm-up

ratio is too low even for the same site navigation. In this CL, after

stopping a service worker, we want to warm it up to prepare for the next

navigation. So the new service worker status transition looks like:



[Warm-up is triggered.]

- kStopped

- kStarting

- WarmedUp



[User navigates to a page.]

- kRunning



[Service worker is not used for 30 seconds.]

- kStopping

- kStopped

- kStarting

- WarmedUp



[The warmed-up Service worker is not used for 10 minutes.]

- kStopping

- kStopped (without no warm-up)

entry.title: Fix the broken tests when AppStorage is enabled(Part 24).
entry.content:
When the AppStorage feature is enabled, AppService blocks the app

publishing until it's ready, after reading from the AppStorage file.

This may break some tests, e.g. AutotestPrivateApiTest.AutotestPrivate.



Because Chrome browser is added to the shelf at a very early stage,

when the Chrome browser app hasn't been added to AppRegistryCache in

AppService. So IsAppPinEditable returns false[1], and

pin_state_forced_by_type = true. This result is different when the

AppStorage feature is disabled, so the test reports error.



Actually, when the Chrome browser is added to the shelf, it is not as

an App, so it won't have the pin/unpin in menu[2]. So we can add a

similar checking for that as well, if the shelf item is not an app

type, don't call IsAppPinEditable to get `pin_state_forced_by_type`.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/ui/ash/shelf/chrome_shelf_controller_util.cc;l=187;drc=67d90538f11c6b232dbfd716075db52aeb34fd15?q=IsAppPinEditable&ss=chromium%2Fchromium%2Fsrc



[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:chrome/browser/ui/ash/shelf/shelf_context_menu.cc;l=140
